04323nam a22007695i 9780824863098DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t19961996hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029820323  a(OCoLC)1032690494  a(OCoLC)1037905907  a(OCoLC)1042037038  a(OCoLC)1046605862  a(OCoLC)1047009587  a(OCoLC)1049636222  a(OCoLC)1054879220  a97808248630987 a10.1515/97808248630982doi  a(DE-B1597)483901  a(OCoLC)1024018333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL809.Z9bA25 1996 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a895.6/3421 aIzumi, Kyoka, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapanese Gothic Tales /cKyoka Izumi. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction THE FAMILIARITY OF STRANGE PLACES -- tThe Surgery Room -- tThe Holy Man of Mount Kōya -- tOne Day in Spring -- tOsen and Sōkichi -- tAfterword: A DISCUSSION OF THE TALES -- tABOUT THE TRANSLATOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aResisting the various forms of realism popular during the Meiji "enlightenment," Izumi Kyoka (1873-1939) was among the most popular writers who continued to work in the old-fashioned genres of fantasy, mystery, and romance. Gothic Tales makes available for the first time a collection of stories by this highly influential writer, whose decadent romanticism led him to envision an idiosyncratic world--a fictive purgatory --precious and bizarre though always genuine despite its melodramatic formality. The four stories presented here are among Kyoka's best-known works. They are drawn from four stages of the author's development, from the "conceptual novels" of 1895 to the fragmented romanticism of his mature work. In the way of introduction, Inouye presents a clear analysis of Kyoka's problematic stature as a "great gothic writer" and emphasizes the importance of Kyoka's work to the present reevaluation of literary history in general and modern Japanese literature in particular. The extensive notes that follow the translation serve as an intelligent guide for the reader, supplying details about each of the stories and how they fit into the pattern of mythic development that allowed Kyoka to deal with his fears in a way that sustained his life and, as Mishima Yukio put it, pushed the Japanese language to its highest potential.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aInouye, Charles Shirō.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486309840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824863098/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK